			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Symbolic Execution of High-Level Transformations</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AhmadSalimAlSibahi.html">Ahmad Salim Al-Sibahi</a>, <a href="../profile/AleksandarSDimovski.html">Aleksandar S. Dimovski</a>, <a href="../profile/AndrzejWąsowski.html">Andrzej Wąsowski</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997382">10.1145/2997364.2997382</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It applies symbolic execution as a formal technique to verify properties of transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> The subject of analysis is high-level transformation programs used in DSL engineering.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Transformations are used to provide semantics (typing/evaluation), often as refinement steps toward executable artifacts.
</li></ul></li></ul>
